Spring Boot + gRPC Server Streaming Explained
      So previously, we understood gRPC unary communication where you send a single request and receive a single response which is similar to the traditional restful request and response
model. 
     Now we discuss about server streaming, imagine you are building an application that needs to
show live updates like tracking stock prices or cricket score. In such cases, server streaming is your best choice. In server streaming pattern, the client send a single request. For example, give
me an update for stock symbol XYZ, then the server respond with a continuous stream of data sending updates as they happen. 
    So in actual server streaming implementation where the value will keep updating the
page without refresh it manually. Your server will emit the event once there is
update happened then your client will face that and will display the value. 

1. In server application we have stock_trading.proto and define a method for server streaming

service StockTradingService{

  // UNARY - RPC -> get current stock price
  rpc getStockPrice(StockRequest) returns (StockResponse);

  //server streaming - we want our server to send stream of data. So instead of sending the single response we'll tell to this gRPC server to send me the stream of stockresponse
  rpc subscribeStockPrice(StockRequest) returns (stream StockResponse);

}

Now client send the request by giving the stockrequest, whenever there will be update on the stock he will get the stream of response 

