3. Now let's define the implementation for this particular RPC methods. 

Now if you observe from the Java perspective what we are returning here stream of stockorder and the input is Stream of tradestatus that is not the reality in gRPC. Whatever there in your method argument that will be your response (ie) TradeStatus and StockOrder will take as a input, that is the rule follow in gRPC. 

@Override
    public StreamObserver<StockOrder> liveTrading(StreamObserver<TradeStatus> responseObserver) {
        
//Since we getting the stockorder asynchronously and we keep sending the tradestatus as response, we return streamobserver with stockorder as a input. We create a dummy tradestatus object because we are not going to connect to the DB or there is no external call
          return new StreamObserver<>() {

            //For every request,we want to return the tradestatus object, so we build TradeStatus
            @Override
            public void onNext(StockOrder order) {
                System.out.println("Received order: " + order);

                String status = "EXECUTED";
                String message = "Order processed successfully";
                if (order.getQuantity() <= 0) {
                    status = "FAILED";
                    message = "Invalid quantity";
                }
                TradeStatus response = TradeStatus.newBuilder()
                        .setOrderId(order.getOrderId())
                        .setStatus(status)
                        .setMessage(message)
                        .setTimestamp(LocalDateTime.now().format(DateTimeFormatter.ISO_DATE_TIME))
                        .build();
                responseObserver.onNext(response);
            }

           //If any error, I'll just add some messages
            @Override
            public void onError(Throwable throwable) {
                System.err.println("Error " + throwable.getMessage());
            }

           //add when task is completed
            @Override
            public void onCompleted() {
                responseObserver.onCompleted();
            }
        };
    }

